Project context
- This repository contains HCDE coursework with small, self-contained weekly exercises.
- Prefer clear, beginner-friendly code and explanations over clever abstractions.

Directory structure
- Keep this directory map accurate. If files/folders are added, renamed, moved, or deleted, update this section in the same change.
- Only include project files/directories (exclude `.git/` internals and temporary OS files).

```
hcde530/
  README.md
  .cursorrules
  .gitignore
  requirements.txt
  Week2/
    demo_responses.csv
    demo_word_count.py
    app_review_summary.py
    dashboard.html
    week2.md
  Week3/
    clean_responses.py
    count_demo_roles.py
    demo_clean_responses.py
    demo_responses_clean.csv
  Week4/
    fetch_ditto_pokeapi.py
    fetch_reviews_category_helpful.py
    fetch_spoonacular_pasta_search.py
    week4.md
  Week5/
    Teen_Mental_Health_Dataset.csv
    teen mental health analysis.ipynb
    week5.md
```

General coding standards
- Keep changes scoped to the requested task; avoid broad refactors unless explicitly asked.
- Preserve existing behavior unless the user asks for a behavior change.
- Use descriptive names and straightforward control flow.
- Add short comments only when logic is not obvious.

Python conventions
- Target Python 3.10+ syntax.
- Prefer small pure functions for data transforms.
- Include `if __name__ == "__main__":` for runnable scripts.
- Use `csv`/`pathlib` from the standard library before adding dependencies.
- Handle file I/O errors with clear user-facing messages.

CSV and analysis workflow
- Assume CSV files may contain quoted commas and newlines; parse robustly.
- Keep raw input files unchanged; write derived outputs to new files.
- When reporting metrics, include both counts and percentages where helpful.
- Make text normalization steps explicit (case, punctuation, stop words).

HTML/CSS/JS dashboard conventions
- Use semantic HTML and keep assets local (no external CDN dependencies unless requested).
- Keep JavaScript framework-free unless the user asks for a library.
- Show loading and error states for CSV/data fetch operations.
- Keep styles readable and responsive with simple layout rules.

Git hygiene
- Do not commit secrets, local env files, or OS artifacts (for example `.DS_Store`).
- Prefer focused commits with clear messages describing intent.
- If generated files are included, mention why they are committed.

Communication expectations
- When making file changes, briefly state what changed and how to run/verify.
- If an instruction is ambiguous, ask one concise clarifying question before risky changes.
- After structural changes, include a one-line note confirming the directory map in this file was reviewed and updated.
